To develop a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file, you can use the following steps:

1. Include standard C++ library headers:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
```
1. Define a class to count occurrences of a word:
```cpp
class WordCounter
{
public:
    std::string word;
    int count;

    WordCounter(const std::string &wordToFind, const std::string &textFilePath) : word(wordToFind), count(0)
    {
        if (textFilePath.empty())
        {
            std::cout << "Error: Text file path cannot be empty.";
            return;
        }

        std::ifstream file(textFilePath);
        if (!file.is_open())
        {
            std::cout << "Error: Unable to open the file.";
            return;
        }

        std::string line;
        while (getline(file, line))
        {
            if (line.find(word) != std::string::npos)
                ++count;
        }
    }

    int countOccurrences() const
    {
        return count;
    }
};
```
1. Define a function to read a text file line by line:
```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <sstream>
#include <cstring>

std::vector<std::string> readFile(const std::string &filePath)
{
    std::vector<std::string> lines;
    std::ifstream file(filePath);
    if (!file.is_open())
    {
        std::cout << "Error: Unable to open the file.";
        return lines;
    }

    std::string line;
    while (getline(file, line))
        lines.push_back(line);

    return lines;
}
```
1. Define a function to print the number of occurrences of a word:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <algorithm>
#include <map>

int main()
{
    std::string wordToFind("specific");
    std::string textFilePath("text_file.txt");
    std::map<std::string, int> counter;

    std::string line;
    std::ifstream file(textFilePath);
    if (!file.is_open())
    {
        std::cout << "Error: Unable to open the file.";
        return 1;
    }

    while (getline(file, line))
    {
        counter[line]++;
    }

    for (const auto &pair : counter)
    {
        if (pair.second > 1)
        {
            std::cout << "Word \"" << pair.first << "\" occurs " << pair.second << " times." << std::endl;
        }
    }

    return 0;
}
```
1. To use the program, open a command prompt and run the following commands:
```
g++ -Wall -o count_word count_word.cpp
./count_word text_file.txt specific
```
Replace "specific" with the word you want to count occurrences of. The program will output the number of occurrences of the specified word in the text file.

A queue can be implemented using two stacks in Python. Here's an example implementation:
```python
class Queue:
    def __init__(self):
        self._stack1 = []
        self._stack2 = []

    def enqueue(self, item):
        self._stack1.append(item)

    def dequeue(self):
        if not self._stack1:
            self._stack2.append(self._stack1.pop())
            return self._stack2.pop()
        else:
            return self._stack1.pop()

    def is_empty(self):
        return not self._stack1
```
This implementation uses two stacks to store the data. The `enqueue` method appends the new item to the top of either `stack1` or `stack2`, depending on whether the other stack is empty. The `dequeue` method dequeues an item from the non-empty stack. The `is_empty` method checks if both stacks are empty.
